Class LinkedListRecursive<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.ncsu.csc216.pack_scheduler.util.LinkedListRecursive<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - generic type parameter

    public class LinkedListRecursive<E>
extends java.lang.Object
    custom implementation of a recursive linked list that doesn't allow for null elements or duplicate elements as defined by the equals() method.
    Author:
    Ben W Ioppolo

      • add

        public boolean add(E element)
        Attempts to add the passed element to the end of the list. If the list already contains the item, an IllegalArgumentException is thrown. If the list is empty, this method adds the item. Otherwise, this method calls the ListNode.Add E method which recursively finds the end of the list and adds the passed element there.
        Parameters:
        element - The element to try adding to the list.
        Returns:
        true if the element is added to the list. false otherwise.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the passed element already exists in the list.

      • add

        public void add(int index,
                E element)
        Adds the passed element data to the specified index location in the list. If the element is null, the element already exists in the list, or if the index is out of bounds, exceptions are thrown. Additionally, if the size of the list is 0 this method adds the element to the list. Otherwise, this methods calls the ListNode.Add(int, E) method which traverses the list recursively and adds the element at the appropriate location.
        Parameters:
        index - The location in the list to add the item.
        element - The data for the new item to add to the list.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if the passed element is null
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the element already exists in the list
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the index is less than 0 or greater than the size of the list.

      • get

        public E get(int index)
        Gets the item in the list located at the specifed index. If the index is out of bounds, an exception is thrown. This methods calls the ListNode.get(int) method which traverses the list recursively and adds the element at the appropriate location.
        Parameters:
        index - The index of the item to retrieve from the list.
        Returns:
        The data that is stored at the index location in the list.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the passed index is less than 0 or greater than the size of the list.

      • remove

        public boolean remove(E element)
        Removes the specified element from the list if it exists in the list and returns true if it is removed and false otherwise. This method can remove the first item from the list if it matches the passed element otherwise it calls the ListNode.remove(E) method to recursively traverse the list and remove the item if a match is found.
        Parameters:
        element - The element to remove if it matches an item in the list
        Returns:
        true if the item is removed and false otherwise.

      • remove

        public E remove(int index)
        Removes the item from the list that is located at the specified index. If the index is out of bounds an exception is thrown. If there is only 1 item in the list, this method removes the item and returns the item that was removed. Otherwise, this method calls the ListNode.remove(int) method which recursively traverses the list to find the item to remove at the index.
        Parameters:
        index - The index of the item to remove from the list
        Returns:
        The item that was removed from the list
        Throws:
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the passed index is less than 0 or greater than the size of the list.

      • set

        public E set(int index,
             E element)
        Writes the passed element data into the list item located at the passed index location. If the index is out of bounds, an exception is thrown. The actual set process is done by ListNode.set method which recursively traverses the list to find the index location.
        Parameters:
        index - The location in the list to write the passed data into.
        element - The data to write into the passed location in the list.
        Returns:
        The item that was in the list location prior to being overwritten.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the passed index is less than 0 or greater than the list size.

      • contains

        public boolean contains(E element)
        Checks if the list contains the passed element. If the list is null or empty then false is returned. Otherwise, the ListNode.contains method is called which recursively checks the list for a match.
        Parameters:
        element - The element to check for existence in the list.
        Returns:
        true if the element is in the list and false otherwise.
